        "The theory of continental drift proposed by Alfred Wegener in the early twentieth century radically challenged prevailing scientific assumptions about the fixed and permanent nature of Earth's landmasses. Wegener observed that the coastlines of South America and Africa appeared to fit together like puzzle pieces and noted striking similarities in fossil records found on both continents. Despite this compelling evidence the scientific community largely dismissed his theory for decades partly because he could not adequately explain the underlying mechanism driving such massive movement. It was not until the mid twentieth century when scientists discovered detailed evidence of seafloor spreading along mid ocean ridges that the theory gained widespread acceptance. This breakthrough led to the development of plate tectonics a comprehensive framework explaining how rigid plates of Earth's crust slowly shift atop the semi molten mantle below. These gradual movements driven by convective currents deep within the earth explain phenomena ranging from earthquakes and volcanic eruptions to the formation of towering mountain ranges. The theory also revealed that continents were once joined together in a supercontinent known as Pangaea before gradually drifting apart over hundreds of millions of years. Modern satellite technology now allows scientists to measure these tectonic movements with extraordinary precision confirming predictions made decades earlier by geologists working with far more limited tools. Plate tectonics stands today as one of the most unifying and foundational theories in all of earth science reshaping our understanding of the planet's dynamic history.",
